data.enText: a clear difference or contrast especially between people or things that are similar or related

data.chText: 传统社会和现代社会的差别
data.enText: distinctions between traditional and modern societies

data.chText: 哲学家过去习惯不把艺术和科学区别开来。
data.enText: Philosophers did not use to make a distinction between arts and science.

data.chText: 我们得把两起事件区别开来。
data.enText: We need to draw a distinction between the two events.
the quality of being excellent or important
the quality of being sth that is special

data.chText: 她不同凡响，是第一个飞越大西洋的女子。
data.enText: She had the distinction of being the first woman to fly the Atlantic.
the separation of people or things into different groups

data.chText: 这项新法律对成人和孩子同等对待。
data.enText: The new law makes no distinction between adults and children (= treats them equally) .

data.chText: 所有团体一律有权得到这笔款项。
data.enText: All groups are entitled to this money without distinction .

data.chText: （尤指给学生的）优等评分，荣誉，奖赏
data.enText: a special mark/grade or award that is given to sb, especially a student, for excellent work

data.chText: 娜奥米的数学得了优等。
data.enText: Naomi got a distinction in maths.

simple_means.memory_skill: dis 分开 + tinct〔= stinct〕刺；刺激 + ion，distinct 的名词 → 区别；优秀

means: （尤指给学生的）优等评分，荣誉，奖赏

ex.chText: 东西方文化习俗之间存在着明显的差异。
ex.enText: There is an obvious contrast between the cultural practices of the East  and the West.

ex.chText: 与她姐姐相比，她似乎更苗条些。
ex.enText: She seems slimmer by contrast with her sister.

synonyms.bx: 指进行比较的人、观点、情况、事物等的不同之处，也指对人或事物之间进行的对比。

ex.enText: The antithesis of selfishness is love.

ex.chText: 他的写作风格与我的完全相反。
ex.enText: His writing style is in complete antithesis to mine.

ex.chText: 白昼和黑夜之间对比明显。
ex.enText: The antithesis between night and day is clear.

synonyms.bx: 指与某事物完全相反的事物，常后接介词 of；也指两事物之间的对比，常后接介词 between。

ex.chText: 这两张图片之间有细微差别。
ex.enText: There is a fine distinction between the two pictures.

ex.chText: 该法令对待男女并无区别。
ex.enText: The Act makes no distinction between men and women.

synonyms.bx: 较正式用词，除指事物的本质差别外，还指在细节方面的差别，须仔细观察、研究后方能察觉，常后接介词 between。

example: he learned the distinction between gold and lead
it has the distinction of being the cheapest restaurant in town

tr: a discrimination between things as different and distinct
example: it is necessary to make a distinction between love and infatuation

tr: high status importance owing to marked superiority

value.def: A distinction between similar things is a difference.

example.ex: There are obvious distinctions between the two wine-making areas...
example.tran: 两个酿酒地区之间有着显著的差别。

example.ex: The distinction between craft and fine art is more controversial.
example.tran: 对手工艺和美术之间的差别争议更大。

defx.def: If you draw a distinction or make a distinction, you say that two things are different.

example.ex: I did not yet make a distinction between the pleasures of reading and of writing fiction...
example.tran: 我还没有搞清楚阅读的快乐和写小说的快乐有何不同。

example.ex: He draws a distinction between art and culture.
example.tran: 他区分了艺术和文化的不同。

value.def: Distinction is the quality of being very good or better than other things of the same type.

example.ex: Lewis emerges as a composer of distinction and sensitivity.
example.tran: 刘易斯作为一位悟性很高的优秀作曲家崭露头角。

value.def: A distinction is a special award or honour that is given to someone because of their very high level of achievement.

example.ex: The order was created in 1902 as a special distinction for eminent men and women...
example.tran: 该勋位设立于1902年，作为一项殊荣授予杰出的男性和女性。

example.ex: I did an M.A. at Liverpool University in Latin American Studies and got a distinction.
example.tran: 我在利物浦大学以优异成绩获得了拉丁美洲研究方向的硕士学位。

value.def: If you say that someone or something has the distinction of being something, you are drawing attention to the fact that they have the special quality of being that thing. Distinction is normally used to refer to good qualities, but can sometimes also be used to refer to bad qualities.

example.ex: He has the distinction of being regarded as the Federal Republic's greatest living writer.
example.tran: 他才华横溢，被誉为联邦共和国目前尚在世的最伟大的作家。

partsOfSpeech.dec: dis 分开 + tinct〔= stinct〕刺；刺激 → 把刺分开后显得清楚的；明显的 → 清楚的；明显的
dis 分开 + tinct〔= stinct〕刺；刺激 + ion，distinct 的名词 → 区别；优秀
dis 分开 + tinct〔= stinct〕刺；刺激 + ive …的 → 有区别的；与众不同的
di〔s〕分离 + stingu 刺；刺激 + ish 使… → 把不同的刺分离 → 区别
distinguish 区别；辨出 + ed 表形容词 → 与众不同的 → 著名的
ex 出 + tinct〔= stinct〕刺；刺激 → 拔出刺 → 灭绝的，注意：ex后接s开头的词根时省略s
extinct 灭绝的 + ion 表名词 → 灭绝
ex 出 + tingu 刺 + ish 使… → 把刺拔出，刺引申为火焰 → 熄灭
in 使… + stig〔= stinct〕刺；刺激 + ate 做，造成，使… → 刺激〔别人〕→ 煽动
in 向内 + stinct 刺；刺激 → 内在的刺激 → 本能
stimul 刺；刺激 + ate 做，造成，使… → 刺激，鼓励
stimul 刺；刺激 + ation 行为，过程，状态，结果 → 刺激，鼓励
sting 刺；刺激 + y …的 → 对钱的事挑刺 → 小气的
